Its perfectly O.K. not to delegate at some point in the tree, or to
delegate some domains at a particular level and not others.  For
example, if you cruise around the NAVY.MIL domain, you will find
undelegated names such as VAXB.NAVY.MIL alongside delegated domains such
as USNA.NAVY.MIL.

However, you cannot put NS and SOA RRs at say, NAVY.MIL, WITHOUT
actuyally delgating it.  I'm not sure whether you were suggesting this
or not in your message, but NS RRs can be though of as making the cut rather
than marking a cut.

Where do you want to make cuts?  This is mostly an issue of what's
convenient for you, but the usual reasons are:

1)	Make zone cuts where you are passing on authority to another
	suborganization.  Note that this is not REQUIRED.  You can
	pass authority right back to yourself if you want to.

2)	Make cuts where it makes for convenient management or use.
	For example, the root node is a zone in itself.  We thought that
	this would be convenient so that we can put "top" level 
	domains in separate master files and zones.

Hope this make it clear.

paul

